moves.1... Nf6 2. c4 e6: White has a two main choices, nc3 and after bb4 we enter the nimzo indian, or nf3 which is queens indian territory.
moves.6. Nbd2: I played this move for a couple of reasons. I wanted to avoid double pawns, and i had seen cabablanca play this move in a similiar position with favorable result.
moves.8... Bd6: Bishop drops back to an active square. Taking the knight only favors white.
moves.9. cxd5 Bxd5: Here i had plan of playing e4 e5 after preparation and maybe go f4 at some point
moves.10. b4 Nbd7 11. Bb2 Rb8 12. Qc2 h6: Here i should have instantly play e4, but gladly my opponent also missed it.
moves.13. Rfe1 Re8 14. e4: And black resigned here. He cant avoid losing a piece. If the bishop moves then e5 with a pawn fork.
